'''''Jiu Manzhou Dang'''''<ref name="book">{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books/?id=B73RAAAAMAAJ | title=Jiu Manzhou dang | volume=Volume 6 | publisher=[[Google Books]] | date=1969 | accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> ({{Zh|c=舊滿洲檔}}) ([[Manchu language|Manchu]]: {{mongolUnicode|ᡶᡝ ᠮᠠᠨᠵᡠ ᡩᠠᠩᠰᡝ}} ''Fe Manju Dangse'') is a set of [[Manchu language|Manchu]] archives stored at the [[National Palace Museum]] in [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]].<ref>{{cite web| url=http://sites.fas.harvard.edu/~mnch210a/tomc.cgi?t=intro | title=Note on the English translation of The Old Manchu Chronicles | first=Mark C. | last=Elliott | publisher=[[Harvard University]] | location=USA | date=2006 | accessdate=20 February 2014}}</ref> It is the sourcebook of ''[[Manwen Laodang]]'' and a primary source of early Manchu history. It is often called ''yuandang'' (原檔 original archives).

It covers official Manchu documents from the 3rd month of the 35th year of the [[Wanli Emperor of China|Wanli Emperor]] (1607) to the 12th month of the 1st year of [[Hong Taiji|Chongde]] (1636).{{fact|date=February 2014}} Archives are mostly written in the script without dots and circles. Although [[Dahai]] is said to have invented the script with dots and circles in 1632, subsequent archives occasionally, but not always, add dots and circles. Standard Manchu required time to establish.

''Jiu Manzhou Dang'' was discovered in 1931, a month after the discovery of the [[Beijing]] edition of ''Manwen Laodang''.{{fact|date=February 2014}} Three more volumes were found in 1935. It was moved from place to place due to long-running wars and was finally carried to Taiwan by the [[Kuomintang]]. The study on original archives was started in 1960s. The National Palace Museum published the copy under the name ''Jiu Manzhou Dang'' in 1969.<ref name="book" />

